    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="85"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d85">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 (Potsdam)/6–2145: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 85 <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HWA2" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the President’s Chief of Staff</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_LFAWD1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d85fn1">Sent by the United States Naval Attaché,
                        Moscow, via Navy channels. Printed from a courtesy copy forwarded to the
                        Department of State.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">routine</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-21">21 June
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>(Personal and top secret for <persName corresp="#p_LFAWD1">Admiral
                        Leahy</persName> from <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>.)</p>
                <p>I will attempt to get <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName>’s reaction
                    to the question contained in your Number 300<note n="2" xml:id="d85fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d79">document No. 79</ref>.</note> as soon as possible. In the
                    meantime for your information I am personally quite sure that <persName
                        corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> not only will have no objection to the
                    Chiefs of Staff accompanying the President but will wish to have intimate talks
                    with the President about the military operations in the Far East which would be
                    possible only if the Chiefs of Staff accompany him. <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2"
                        >Stalin</persName> will of course wish first to discuss the political
                    aspects.</p>
                <p>Am I right in assuming that the Chiefs of Staff will wish to bring only a small
                    staff and not such large numbers as at Yalta? In this connection I feel it
                    important that <persName corresp="#p_DMGJR1">General Deane</persName>, <persName
                        corresp="#p_MRAHL1">Admiral Maples</persName> and <persName
                        corresp="#p_RBGWL1">General Ritchie</persName> come from Moscow and I hope
                    that <persName corresp="#p_MGAGC1">General Marshall</persName> will decide to
                    bring General <persName corresp="#p_RF1">Roberts</persName>, recently returned
                    to Washington from Moscow, if his new duties do not prevent, as the question of
                    lend lease aid may also come up. I feel it would be helpful if one of the
                    following were also present: <persName corresp="#p_SMGSP1">General
                        Spalding</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_YMGJY1">General York</persName>,
                    or <persName corresp="#p_WMGCM1">General Wesson</persName>.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
        </body>
